🔍 1. EDA (Exploratory Data Analysis)

✅ 1.1 Basic Inspection

You checked structure and overview:

df.shape → number of rows & columns
df.head() → first few records
df.info() → data types + null values
df.describe() → statistical summary
df.columns → column names

👉 Purpose:

Understand dataset size
Identify numeric vs categorical features
Check data quality

✅ 1.2 Missing Values Check
df.isnull().sum()

👉 Result:

No missing values found

👉 Purpose:

Decide if imputation is needed (not needed here)

✅ 1.3 Univariate Analysis (Single Feature Analysis)
📊 Numerical Features

Histograms using:

sns.histplot(df[col], kde=True)

👉 Purpose:

Understand distribution (normal/skewed)
Detect outliers visually
📊 Categorical Features

Count plots:

sns.countplot(x=df['sex'])
sns.countplot(x=df['smoker'])
sns.countplot(x=df['children'])

👉 Purpose:

Understand class distribution
Detect imbalance

✅ 1.4 Outlier Detection

Boxplots:

sns.boxplot(x=df[col])

👉 Purpose:

Identify extreme values (especially in BMI, charges)
✅ 1.5 Correlation Analysis

Heatmap:

sns.heatmap(df.corr(numeric_only=True), annot=True)

👉 Purpose:

Understand relationships between features
Identify strong predictors (like smoker vs charges)

🧹 2. Data Cleaning
✅ 2.1 Copy Dataset
df_cleaned = df.copy()

👉 Prevent modifying original data

✅ 2.2 Remove Duplicates
df_cleaned.drop_duplicates(inplace=True)

👉 Purpose:

Avoid bias due to repeated rows
✅ 2.3 Re-check Nulls
df_cleaned.isnull().sum()

👉 Ensures clean dataset before processing

⚙️ 3. Feature Engineering



✅ 3.1 Encoding Categorical Variables
🔹 Label Encoding (Binary)
df_cleaned['sex'] = df_cleaned['sex'].map({"male":0, "female":1})
df_cleaned['smoker'] = df_cleaned['smoker'].map({"no":0, "yes":1})

👉 Converted:

sex → is_female
smoker → is_smoker

👉 Why:

ML models need numeric input
✅ 3.2 Renaming Columns
df_cleaned.rename(columns={
    'sex':'is_female',
    'smoker':'is_smoker'
})

👉 Makes features more meaningful

✅ 3.3 One-Hot Encoding (Nominal Feature)
pd.get_dummies(df_cleaned, columns=['region'], drop_first=True)

👉 Converts:

region → multiple binary columns

👉 Why:

Avoid ordinal assumption
drop_first=True avoids dummy variable trap
✅ 3.4 Type Conversion
df_cleaned = df_cleaned.astype(int)

👉 Ensures consistent numeric format

✅ 3.5 Feature Creation (BMI Category) ⭐
df_cleaned['bmi_category'] = pd.cut(
    df_cleaned['bmi'],
    bins=[0,18.5,24.9,29.9,float('inf')],
    labels=['Underweight','Normal','Overweight','Obese']
)

👉 New Feature Created:

Converts continuous BMI → categorical groups

👉 Why:

Helps model capture non-linear patterns
✅ 3.6 Encoding New Feature
pd.get_dummies(df_cleaned, columns=['bmi_category'], drop_first=True)

👉 Converts BMI categories into ML-friendly format

📏 4. Feature Scaling
scaler = StandardScaler()
df_cleaned[['age','bmi','children']] = scaler.fit_transform(...)

👉 Purpose:

Normalize features (mean = 0, std = 1)

👉 Why:

Important for models like:
Linear Regression
KNN
SVM
🧠 5. Feature Selection
✅ 5.1 Pearson Correlation (Numerical Features)
pearsonr(feature, charges)

👉 Measures:

Linear relationship with target (charges)

👉 Output:

Correlation coefficient (-1 to +1)

👉 Use:

Select strong predictors
✅ 5.2 Chi-Square Test (Categorical Features)
Step 1: Create target bins
df_cleaned['charges_bin'] = pd.qcut(df_cleaned['charges'], q=4)

👉 Converts continuous target → categorical

Step 2: Apply Chi-Square
chi2_contingency(contingency_table)

👉 Purpose:

Check dependency between categorical feature & target

👉 Decision Rule:

p < 0.05 → Important feature
p ≥ 0.05 → Not useful
🎯 6. Final Feature Selection
final_df = df_cleaned[
    ['age','is_female','bmi','children','is_smoker',
     'charges','region_southeast','bmi_category_Obese']
]

👉 Selected:

Most impactful features only

👉 Why:

Reduce noise
Improve model performance
